properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow changing to ice pellets and freezing rain, followed by strong winds and flurries. Further snowfall: 10 cm. Location: Iles-de-la-Madeleine. Time span: today through Saturday morning. Remarks: A low pressure system approaching from the southwest will bring a mix of precipitation and strong winds to the Islands today through Saturday morning. Periods of snow will become mixed with ice pellets this afternoon, then change through freezing rain and rain and back to snow tonight. Forecast guidance indicates that the area of heaviest snowfall from the low pressure system will remain west of the Islands. The snow is expected to taper off to flurries Saturday morning. A wind warning has been issued for strong northwesterly winds forecast to develop tonight as the system moves across the Gulf of St. Lawrence. This wind will cause reduced visibility in snow and blowing snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Total snowfall: 25 to 40 cm (western Newfoundland) and 15 to 30 cm (Great Northern Peninsula).
